:["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lamore","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aime, Rejeanne, Sylviane.","Altered form of French   Lemaire   (via the intermediate form <i>Lemare</i>; compare   Lemar   and   Lamar   2) and possibly also of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname.","French (<b>Lamoré</b>): nickname for a lover or ladykiller, from <i>amoré</i> ‘beloved’, with fused definite article <i>l'</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lemaire","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Fernand, Dominique, Marcel, Armand, Auguste, Aurelien, Chantel, Constant, Cyrille, Emile.","French (mainly northern), Walloon, and Flemish: status name or occupational name for a maire (‘mayor’), a title denoting a municipal magistrate or other local official (the role of the maire differed at different times at different places), or a nickname for someone thought to resemble a maire, from Old French <i>mair(e)</i>, with fused French masculine definite article <i>le</i>. It may also be a nickname for an eldest son, from the same word. Compare   Lamar  ,   Lamer  ,   Lamore  ,   Lemar  , and   Maire  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":5,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":50,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes De Lamore was born in 1332, in Wootton Wawen, Warwickshire, England, her father, Sir Stephen De Lamore, was 25 and her mother, Alice Seymour, was 32. She married Thomas Beaupenny Burgess Of Parliament in Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1400, in Warwickshire, England, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1332–1400":"1332–1400","1326–1410":"1326–1410","1353–1419":"1353–1419","1354–1410":"1354–1410","1307–1370":"1307–1370","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1337":"1337","1326":"1326","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","1410":"1410","1332":"1332","1354":"1354","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1419":"1419","1307":"1307","Wootton Wawen, Warwickshire, England":"Wootton Wawen, Warwickshire, England","Warwickshir